WEBVTT

00:24.190 --> 00:25.649
Hold it right there.

00:28.820 --> 00:29.945
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

00:32.698 --> 00:34.033
Hold it again. Hold it.

00:34.576 --> 00:36.910
Oh, come on, Paul.

00:40.040 --> 00:42.332
One more. One more.

00:47.756 --> 00:49.715
You're not gonna show those to anyone,
are you?

00:49.883 --> 00:51.175
- Sure. Why not?
- Ugh.

00:51.342 --> 00:52.843
- You've got a prime figure.
- Heh.

00:53.053 --> 00:54.803
- You really have, you know.
- Heh.

00:54.971 --> 00:56.513
That's a euphemism for fat.

01:07.150 --> 01:08.525
You wanna go back to the hotel?

01:09.944 --> 01:11.862
What's the matter with right here?

01:13.990 --> 01:15.365
We're too civilized.

01:17.452 --> 01:19.870
I remember when we weren't.

01:20.997 --> 01:22.998
But we'll go back to the hotel.

01:30.673 --> 01:33.008
JOANNA:
Paul, I don't wanna go back home.

01:41.768 --> 01:43.769
[BAND PLAYING HAWAIIAN FOLK MUSIC]

01:54.697 --> 01:58.200
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Trans World Airlines passengers on TW76...

01:58.368 --> 02:01.620
...from Honolulu to New York should
proceed from the check-in counter...

02:01.788 --> 02:03.872
...to the Friendship Lounge for boarding.

02:39.450 --> 02:42.369
[CAR HORNS HONKING]

04:48.454 --> 04:51.123
Wanna know what happened
while you and Joanna were living it up...

04:51.291 --> 04:53.625
...in Maui or Kaui or Yaui, whatever it is?
- What?

04:53.793 --> 04:55.544
There were 15 murders the first week...

04:55.712 --> 04:58.964
...and 21 last week in this goddamn city.
- That's a lot.

04:59.507 --> 05:02.634
You know, decent people are gonna have
to work here and live somewhere else.

05:02.802 --> 05:05.721
PAUL: By "decent people," you mean people
who can afford to live somewhere else.

05:05.888 --> 05:09.599
SAM: Oh, Christ.
You are such a bleeding-heart liberal, Paul.

05:09.809 --> 05:12.561
My heart bleeds a little
for the underprivileged, yeah.

05:12.729 --> 05:16.189
The underprivileged are beating our
goddamn brains out. You know what I say?

05:16.357 --> 05:19.526
Stick them in concentration camps.
That's what I say.

05:19.736 --> 05:21.445
PAUL: Henry.
- Hello.

05:21.654 --> 05:26.158
I've been running a cost-and-profit on
the Jainchill development in Tucson, Arizona.

05:27.076 --> 05:29.286
Well, based on these figures...

05:29.454 --> 05:32.456
...I don't see how Blue Ridge
can underwrite 50 percent of it.

05:33.166 --> 05:36.084
Well, Jainchill's been very successful,
in a small way.

05:37.837 --> 05:40.756
Well, then I suggest
you send a man down...

05:40.923 --> 05:43.425
...from our San Francisco office
to step it out.

05:43.593 --> 05:45.677
Redesign it, if necessary.

05:46.220 --> 05:49.473
Because that's a high risk
for the acreage involved.

05:50.433 --> 05:52.309
I'll talk to Inge about it.
Thanks, Paul.

05:54.103 --> 05:59.816
Oh, uh, Paul, how does it feel
to be back in the war zone after Hawaii?

06:00.902 --> 06:03.362
I was feeling pretty good
until I ran into Sam...

06:03.571 --> 06:06.531
...and he delivered the crime rate statistics.

06:06.699 --> 06:09.034
What this city needs
is more cops than people.

06:09.243 --> 06:13.163
You'll have to find other options, Samuel.
No one could pay the taxes.

06:13.331 --> 06:14.373
[ALL CHUCKLE]

06:16.918 --> 06:18.919
[EASY-LISTENING MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

06:26.302 --> 06:28.095
[MAN WHOOPING]

06:30.890 --> 06:32.891
[SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

06:54.122 --> 06:55.455
$2.17.

06:56.165 --> 06:58.875
Would you have these delivered,
please, Mary?

06:59.877 --> 07:00.961
WOMAN:
Goodbye.

07:17.019 --> 07:19.020
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

08:29.342 --> 08:31.468
Hey, I'm gonna do a thing.

08:32.470 --> 08:34.346
Shit, man. Got business.

08:34.514 --> 08:35.972
Let's go, man.

08:59.288 --> 09:00.705
I'll get it.

09:08.798 --> 09:09.965
Who is it?

09:10.341 --> 09:11.633
Groceries, ma'am.

09:19.350 --> 09:20.976
[LOCK CLICKS]

09:22.562 --> 09:23.812
[CAROL SCREAMING]

09:31.988 --> 09:34.114
Nobody gets hurt, Mother.
Just hold still. Don't move.

09:34.323 --> 09:35.407
What do you want?

09:35.575 --> 09:37.909
Don't jive, Mother. You know what we want.

09:38.119 --> 09:40.787
JOANNA: He's not gonna hurt us?
MAN 1: Not if you got money.

09:42.623 --> 09:43.915
Nobody, nobody.

09:47.003 --> 09:50.297
Hey, Mother.
Look at the artiste doing his art.

09:50.464 --> 09:53.091
- Ain't that beautiful, Mother?
- My purse is in the kitchen.

09:53.259 --> 09:54.759
Just stand still.

09:55.303 --> 09:58.179
We'll do as they say, Carol.
Where is your purse?

10:06.480 --> 10:10.900
- Shit, you only got four bucks.
- I got three, and two bits.

10:11.235 --> 10:13.778
You're gonna get
the shit kicked out of you, Mother.

10:14.530 --> 10:16.781
- It's all we have.
- Rich people like you?

10:16.949 --> 10:20.035
- Shit, we want money, Mother. Now get it!
- It's true. That's all we...

10:20.244 --> 10:21.953
[JOANNA SCREAMS]

10:22.872 --> 10:25.332
- How'd you like to get fucked?
- No!

10:26.125 --> 10:27.834
I'm gonna stick you in the ass.

10:28.044 --> 10:29.586
[CAROL SCREAMING]

10:32.923 --> 10:33.965
Leave her alone!

10:37.887 --> 10:39.596
Goddamn rich cunt!

10:40.222 --> 10:41.431
I kill rich cunts.

10:42.308 --> 10:44.559
Mother's getting
the shit kicked out of her.

10:54.862 --> 10:56.863
MAN 2:
Hey, let's screw this one, man. Huh?

10:57.073 --> 11:00.450
MAN 1: No, man. Let's travel.
- No, man. Let me paint her ass.

11:00.743 --> 11:01.910
[MAN 3 LAUGHS MANIACALLY]

11:02.119 --> 11:03.787
[CLOTHES RIPPING]

11:05.206 --> 11:07.207
[MEN LAUGHING]

11:09.710 --> 11:12.962
Hey, man. You think you're an artiste?
I'll show you how to paint, man.

11:13.130 --> 11:15.090
I'm gonna paint her goddamn mouth!

11:15.883 --> 11:18.635
MAN 2: He's gonna paint your mouth.
You're gonna like that.

11:19.095 --> 11:21.513
MAN 1: You get any ideas about biting
my paintbrush, you'll get what Mother got.

11:21.681 --> 11:24.349
- You're gonna swallow that paint.
MAN 1: She'll swallow the paint.

11:24.558 --> 11:26.184
Open that goddamn throat!

11:28.270 --> 11:30.355
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

11:35.403 --> 11:37.404
Mother's going for the phone!

11:39.365 --> 11:41.282
Shit, let's split.

12:07.184 --> 12:09.144
Thelma, will you get my wife
on the phone, please?

12:09.311 --> 12:11.062
[PHONE RINGS]

12:11.230 --> 12:12.397
Mr. Kersey's office.

12:16.235 --> 12:17.694
[INTERCOM BUZZES]

12:19.488 --> 12:22.574
- Is it my wife?
THELMA: No, sir. It's your son-in-law.

12:24.118 --> 12:25.493
Hello, Jack.

12:25.703 --> 12:26.953
Dad.

12:28.038 --> 12:29.080
Dad, we got trouble.

12:29.290 --> 12:30.999
Trouble? You and Carol?

12:31.208 --> 12:32.333
Don't tell me about it.

12:32.543 --> 12:34.252
No, no. Dad...

12:35.421 --> 12:37.297
It's Mom and Carol.

12:37.965 --> 12:40.675
They're taking them to the emergency
receiving at Canal Hospital.

12:40.843 --> 12:43.511
- What the hell for?
- Look, I don't know.

12:43.721 --> 12:45.555
The police just called me.

12:45.765 --> 12:47.140
What's happening, Jack?

12:47.308 --> 12:49.184
I don't know any more than that, Dad.

12:49.393 --> 12:53.062
Look, I'm at my office, I'm going to
the hospital, just meet me there, okay?

12:55.858 --> 12:58.735
WOMAN 1 [OVER PA]:
Dr. Fanning, go to the emergency room, stat.

12:58.903 --> 13:01.488
Dr. Fanning, go to the emergency room.

13:01.655 --> 13:03.072
WOMAN 2:
Dr. Diaz...

13:03.949 --> 13:05.408
How are they? Are they all right?

13:05.576 --> 13:07.744
I don't know. I just got here
a few minutes ago.

13:07.995 --> 13:10.830
Do you know anything?
Were they cut, stabbed, what?

13:10.998 --> 13:12.040
I...

13:12.208 --> 13:14.209
No, sir. Just beat up.

13:14.585 --> 13:18.046
This is Officer Joe Charles, he came
in the ambulance with Mom and Carol.

13:18.214 --> 13:20.840
PAUL: They gonna be all right?
- I've told Mr. Toby all I know.

13:21.258 --> 13:24.010
If there's anything I can do,
ask for me at the 21 st precinct.

13:24.178 --> 13:25.470
Good luck to you.

13:26.263 --> 13:27.931
Come on, Dad.
We might as well go sit down.

13:28.098 --> 13:29.265
What'd they tell you?

13:30.643 --> 13:31.851
JACK:
Not much.

13:32.061 --> 13:33.102
PAUL:
Yeah, but what?

13:35.272 --> 13:36.606
They beat them both up.

13:36.774 --> 13:40.777
- Who did? Why?
- Take it easy, Dad. I'm just as rattled as you are.

13:41.654 --> 13:44.948
The officer said that Carol
wasn't making much sense.

13:45.157 --> 13:47.200
Two, maybe three men, they...

13:47.618 --> 13:49.160
She opened the door to let them in...

13:49.328 --> 13:52.080
...because she thought it was
the delivery boy from the supermarket.

13:54.291 --> 13:56.125
Jesus God.

13:56.293 --> 13:58.294
[MAN & WOMAN 3
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY OVER PA]

14:00.756 --> 14:02.549
When are we gonna know something?

14:02.716 --> 14:05.927
WOMAN 1 [OVER PA]: Will the following
doctors go to the emergency room, stat:

14:06.095 --> 14:07.345
Dr. White...

14:07.513 --> 14:09.222
They know we're here?

14:09.723 --> 14:13.226
JACK: The nurses know. I spoke to one of them.
PAUL: Somebody ought to come.

14:13.394 --> 14:16.688
There's a man over there.
He's bleeding, and nobody comes.

14:19.900 --> 14:23.611
Nurse, we're waiting to find out
what happened to my wife and daughter.

14:23.779 --> 14:26.781
A doctor will see you
after he's made his examination.

14:26.949 --> 14:28.867
PAUL:
But we've been waiting a long time.

14:29.201 --> 14:32.245
It hasn't been that long, Dad,
just two or three minutes.

14:35.666 --> 14:37.292
- Mr. Toby?
- Yes.

14:37.459 --> 14:38.793
Your wife is all right.

14:39.003 --> 14:40.879
We've sedated her and put her to bed.

14:41.088 --> 14:43.214
My name is Paul Kersey.
How's my wife?

14:45.050 --> 14:46.217
I'm sorry.

14:46.427 --> 14:48.970
She died a few minutes ago, Mr. Kersey.

14:55.102 --> 14:58.605
MAN: Almighty God, we commend
to you our neighbor Joanna...

14:58.814 --> 15:01.107
...trusting your love and mercy...

15:01.317 --> 15:05.069
...and believing in the promise
of a resurrection to eternal life...

15:05.279 --> 15:09.282
...through our Lord Jesus Christ. Amen.

15:10.117 --> 15:15.163
Almighty God, father of the whole family
in heaven and on earth...

15:15.331 --> 15:17.457
...stand by those who sorrow...

15:17.666 --> 15:21.210
...that as they lean on your strength,
they may be upheld...

15:21.378 --> 15:24.380
...and believe the good news
of life beyond life...

15:24.590 --> 15:28.927
...through Jesus Christ, our lord. Amen.

15:46.987 --> 15:48.947
I'm going back with Sam and Adele.

15:49.114 --> 15:50.990
They go right by my place.

15:52.201 --> 15:54.035
Don't you wanna come to our apartment?

15:54.203 --> 15:57.246
It's time I went to my own,
I have to sometime.

16:00.834 --> 16:03.836
Baby?

16:05.422 --> 16:07.548
I'm going back with Sam.

16:07.967 --> 16:09.717
You get plenty of rest.

16:16.600 --> 16:18.476
She'll be all right, Dad.

16:36.453 --> 16:38.371
[CAR HORN HONKING]

16:47.756 --> 16:49.590
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]:
Residents of northern suburbs...

16:49.758 --> 16:52.468
...will need quite some time to dig
themselves out of a snowstorm...

16:52.636 --> 16:54.178
...that's taking much of Connecticut...

16:54.346 --> 16:56.556
...and Rockland and Westchester
Counties by surprise.

16:56.890 --> 16:57.932
In New York City...

16:58.100 --> 17:00.184
...light snow flurries lingering
till about midnight.

17:00.352 --> 17:02.520
- No accumulation, but afternoon...
- Turn that thing off.

17:02.688 --> 17:06.273
MAN 2: I'm listening to the weather. Why haven't
you found my dog? He's vital to my income.

17:06.442 --> 17:09.109
He paints such marvelous
pictures with his paws.

17:12.531 --> 17:15.782
OFFICER 1: Yes. Help you?
PAUL: Where can I find Officer Joe Charles?

17:15.992 --> 17:18.786
- What's your business?
- Well, my name is Paul Kersey.

17:18.996 --> 17:21.580
A couple days ago,
my wife and daughter were attacked...

17:21.749 --> 17:24.584
...and he was one of the policemen
on the scene, I wanna talk to him.

17:26.211 --> 17:28.253
MAN 3:
Yeah, well, okay, so I think the...

17:28.422 --> 17:32.175
Hattie, is Joe Charles still back there
or has he gone on duty yet?

17:32.634 --> 17:35.053
Yeah, there's someone out here
who wants to talk to him.

17:35.220 --> 17:37.805
WOMAN: I told you somebody...
- Have a seat. He'll be right out.

17:38.015 --> 17:40.433
...snatched my purse!
The man came up from behind me.

17:40.601 --> 17:43.603
My credit cards is in there,
my rent money, I don't have no key.

17:43.771 --> 17:45.396
- Do I have a description?
OFFICER 2: Yes.

17:45.564 --> 17:48.024
The man came from behind me!

17:48.192 --> 17:50.109
OFFICER 2: You didn't see who it was?
WOMAN: No, I didn't see!

17:50.277 --> 17:53.279
- Hello, Mr. Kersey.
- Officer Charles.

17:53.530 --> 17:57.909
I dropped by to see if you had any information
on the people who attacked my family.

17:58.077 --> 18:00.661
I'll take you to the detective
in charge of the case.

18:10.547 --> 18:12.840
- Uh, lieutenant?
- Yeah.

18:13.008 --> 18:16.719
This is Mr. Paul Kersey, case number 884.
His wife and daughter were assaulted.

18:16.929 --> 18:19.097
- Glad to know you, Mr. Kersey.
- I'm going on duty now...

18:19.264 --> 18:20.681
...so I'll leave.
- Thanks, officer.

18:20.849 --> 18:22.475
- Not at all.
- Right this way, Mr. Kersey.

18:23.227 --> 18:24.936
Will you have a seat, Mr. Kersey?

18:27.106 --> 18:29.065
Have you found out anything yet?

18:29.441 --> 18:32.568
Well, the supermarket security officer
and one of the checkers...

18:32.736 --> 18:36.155
...remembers these three characters leaving
right after Mrs. Kersey and your daughter.

18:36.323 --> 18:39.909
They think they could've gotten the apartment
number off the address on the grocery bags...

18:40.077 --> 18:42.870
...but they haven't been able to pick
the faces out of the mug book.

18:43.247 --> 18:45.414
How is your daughter, Mr. Kersey?

18:45.582 --> 18:48.167
She's under doctor's sedation right now.

18:48.919 --> 18:53.089
But today I had the funeral
for my wife up in Connecticut...

18:53.257 --> 18:54.590
...and she was able to make that.

18:55.300 --> 18:58.344
Your daughter didn't give us
much information, Mr. Kersey.

18:58.512 --> 19:00.680
We wish we could persuade her
to look at the mug books.

19:01.723 --> 19:02.974
Did she refuse?

19:03.851 --> 19:06.435
Her husband asked us
to wait for a few days.

19:06.603 --> 19:08.604
In fact, the sooner
she looks at the mug books...

19:08.772 --> 19:11.941
...the better chance she has
of recalling one or two of the faces.

19:12.568 --> 19:15.528
Well, I'll talk to my son-in-law...

19:15.946 --> 19:18.698
...and see what can be done.
- I'd appreciate that, Mr. Kersey.

19:18.866 --> 19:20.867
[PAUL SIGHS]

19:21.326 --> 19:23.286
Any chance of catching these men?

19:24.204 --> 19:26.038
There's a chance, sure.

19:27.166 --> 19:28.457
Just a chance?

19:28.667 --> 19:31.335
I'd be less than honest
if I gave you more hope, Mr. Kersey.

19:32.212 --> 19:35.423
In the city, that's the way it is.

19:47.060 --> 19:48.936
I thought you were asleep.

19:50.439 --> 19:52.523
[SCREAMS]

19:52.983 --> 19:54.984
MAN [ON TV]:
Are you getting the most out of life?

19:55.652 --> 19:58.571
Are you satisfied, fulfilled, happy?

19:58.864 --> 20:01.365
Our bank has helped many to a better future.

20:01.533 --> 20:02.575
[TV TURNS OFF]

20:28.143 --> 20:29.644
[OBJECT CLATTERS]

20:57.089 --> 20:58.714
- Good morning, Mr. Kersey.
- Morning.

20:59.549 --> 21:02.760
Would you give me
$20 in quarters, please?

21:15.065 --> 21:16.190
[DOOR OPENS]

21:17.526 --> 21:19.318
- Good morning, Paul.
- Morning.

21:20.112 --> 21:21.153
[SAM SIGHS]

21:21.321 --> 21:23.572
Paul, you're tough.
You know, you really are.

21:23.740 --> 21:25.366
I told Ives you'd come in this morning.

21:25.534 --> 21:29.537
I said, "Paul is not the kind of man
to leave the pieces of his life lying around.

21:29.705 --> 21:31.497
He'll just start picking them up."

21:31.665 --> 21:34.000
Just a matter of keeping busy, Sam.

21:36.086 --> 21:38.379
Paul, welcome back.

21:38.547 --> 21:40.506
- Good morning, Henry.
- See you for lunch, Paul?

21:40.674 --> 21:43.592
- Yeah, sure.
- Paul, I'm gonna give you a vacation.

21:43.760 --> 21:45.553
From New York, that is.

21:45.929 --> 21:50.099
The Jainchill development
of Tucson, Arizona.

21:50.350 --> 21:53.853
I want you to take it over.
Redesign it, if necessary.

21:54.021 --> 21:56.355
Whatever you have to do.
All right?

21:56.773 --> 21:59.775
That's all right, but can I give you
an answer in about a week?

21:59.943 --> 22:02.653
I don't wanna leave New York
just now because of Carol.

22:02.988 --> 22:04.030
Fine.

22:04.239 --> 22:06.449
When you're ready, let me know.

22:06.908 --> 22:10.202
Beautiful place, Tucson.
They can breathe out there.

22:19.296 --> 22:21.464
She's sleeping too much.

22:22.341 --> 22:23.924
It's not normal.

22:24.509 --> 22:27.511
I've got a couple of TV dinners
in the oven. Come on.

22:27.679 --> 22:29.305
It'll just be a couple of minutes.

22:30.807 --> 22:32.850
Jack, this drink's enough for me.

22:33.810 --> 22:36.812
- I've never seen you drink without eating.
- I'm not hungry.

22:37.981 --> 22:42.818
I think maybe you ought to
take Carol to see another doctor.

22:43.487 --> 22:47.239
I, uh... I did. Today. A psychiatrist.

22:48.283 --> 22:52.411
He seems to feel it might help her
if I took her away to another environment.

22:53.246 --> 22:56.582
Out of New York, on the shore someplace.

22:56.792 --> 22:58.501
Sounds like a good idea.

22:58.668 --> 23:01.921
- I'll go along with you.
- Uh... No, Dad. He...

23:02.297 --> 23:06.842
He seemed to feel that it might be better if
she didn't have any association with anyone...

23:07.010 --> 23:10.805
...that might remind her of that day.
- How the hell do I remind her of that day?

23:11.181 --> 23:12.973
JACK:
Well, you know how it is, Dad.

23:13.308 --> 23:15.601
I mean, it happened in your apartment.

23:15.977 --> 23:20.356
And you're living there.
You remind her of Mom.

23:22.567 --> 23:25.569
Dad, don't make it tough for me.

23:26.738 --> 23:29.573
Okay, I'll make it easy for you.

23:29.825 --> 23:33.494
Ives asked me to go to
Tucson, Arizona on a job.

23:33.703 --> 23:37.790
- How long will you be gone?
- I don't know. Until I look the job over.

23:38.375 --> 23:40.918
But you call me every other day,
let me know how Carol is.

23:41.420 --> 23:43.504
Sure I will, Dad.

23:44.756 --> 23:48.426
You know, that'll be good for you,
I hear Tucson's a really beautiful place.

23:48.593 --> 23:50.428
Yeah, yeah. That's what everybody says.

23:58.603 --> 24:00.813
MAN 1:
How are you today, sir?

24:45.358 --> 24:47.067
MAN 2:
Son of a bitch.

24:47.360 --> 24:49.653
Turn around, son of a bitch.

24:50.030 --> 24:52.323
Motherfucker! I said turn around.

24:52.741 --> 24:54.408
And hand me the money.

26:20.996 --> 26:22.371
Paul Kersey.

26:22.622 --> 26:24.957
- Yeah.
- Aimes Jainchill.

26:25.166 --> 26:26.625
How do you do, Mr. Jainchill?

26:26.793 --> 26:29.128
Aimes. I'll call you Paul.
Come on. Let's get your bags.

26:29.296 --> 26:32.256
- How did you know who I was?
- Well, you look like a New Yorker.

26:32.757 --> 26:34.758
[CATTLE MOOING]

26:40.932 --> 26:42.224
Ho!

26:45.228 --> 26:47.521
Ho. Ho, ho.

26:48.982 --> 26:51.191
Howdy, Jud.

26:58.325 --> 27:03.579
I wanted you to see this country before
you looked at the drawings back at the office.

27:03.955 --> 27:05.623
Give you a better idea.

27:05.999 --> 27:07.708
I don't wanna change these hills.

27:07.876 --> 27:10.169
Don't wanna bulldoze them flat.

27:12.756 --> 27:14.923
You'll waste a lot of building space.

27:15.717 --> 27:18.677
Ha, ha! Wasting space.

27:18.928 --> 27:21.096
Now, those are some words
that you big developers...

27:21.264 --> 27:23.974
...have got to change
for something else.

27:24.142 --> 27:25.351
Such as?

27:25.518 --> 27:27.353
Well, space for life.

27:28.146 --> 27:32.524
Like old Jud up there.
Space for people, horses, cows.

27:33.485 --> 27:36.445
I got funny ideas about building things.

27:43.912 --> 27:46.997
Howdy, folks, welcome to old Tucson,
the famous movie location and studio.

27:47.207 --> 27:48.248
In just a few moments...

27:48.416 --> 27:51.877
Unh. Come on. Let's wet our whistle
before I trot you back to the motel.

27:52.045 --> 27:53.253
Glass of beer, maybe.

27:53.463 --> 27:56.048
- Take their positions on the porches
of the Red Dog Cafe...

27:56.257 --> 27:59.051
...the Territorial Gunsmith shop...
- What's happening here?

27:59.219 --> 28:01.470
Oh, it's a phony western town.

28:01.805 --> 28:05.724
They shoot movies here sometimes,
but the rest of the time, it's for the tourists.

28:06.309 --> 28:09.395
ANNOUNCER: This is where
the actual performance will take place.

28:09.604 --> 28:12.439
- These fellas are pretty good. Wanna watch?
- Sure.

28:12.649 --> 28:14.483
ANNOUNCER:
- Where the Wild West lives again.

28:15.860 --> 28:17.945
MAN 1: Where's the marshal?
MAN 2: He's in the bank.

28:18.154 --> 28:20.072
I spotted him through the window
as I came by.

28:20.240 --> 28:23.701
MAN 1: What have you got in mind to do, then?
MAN 2: Well, why don't you steal my horse?

28:23.868 --> 28:25.869
MAN 1:
All right. That's a good trick. We'll use it.

28:26.037 --> 28:29.665
You spot yourself on the porch
while I draw the marshal out into the open.

28:30.083 --> 28:31.834
Marshal! Hey, marshal!

28:32.043 --> 28:33.669
MARSHAL:
What's the matter, fella?

28:33.920 --> 28:35.546
MAN 1:
Somebody stole my horse.

28:35.755 --> 28:38.048
MARSHAL:
I told you to get out of town by sunset.

28:38.258 --> 28:41.093
MAN 2: You missing a bay mare
that was tied to the hitching rail?

28:41.261 --> 28:43.679
Saw a feller come and take her
just a spell ago.

28:43.888 --> 28:45.556
MARSHAL:
Well, what did he look like?

28:45.765 --> 28:48.225
MAN 2: Well, he was about
this tall, and he had this...

28:48.393 --> 28:49.852
MAN 1:
Get him, Frank!

29:03.241 --> 29:04.324
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

29:13.460 --> 29:18.255
Let's put him inside here and get to
the bank and make that withdrawal.

29:23.094 --> 29:25.804
MARSHAL:
All right, boys. The fun's over.

29:26.347 --> 29:29.266
Throw out your guns
and step out with your hands up.

29:29.476 --> 29:32.895
MAN 1: You'd better listen, marshal.
I've got three sticks of dynamite here.

29:33.062 --> 29:34.146
Don't be a fool.

29:35.315 --> 29:36.648
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

29:51.122 --> 29:53.624
ANNOUNCER: The outlaw life
seemed a shortcut to easy money...

29:53.833 --> 29:57.461
...which could buy liquor, women,
and a turn at the gambling table...

29:57.629 --> 29:59.797
...but there were honest men with dreams...

29:59.964 --> 30:02.591
...who would fight to protect their...
- Let's get that beer.

30:02.759 --> 30:06.845
ANNOUNCER: And who were to plant
the roots that would grow into a nation.

30:13.144 --> 30:15.062
Blue Ridge won't buy it.

30:17.315 --> 30:20.776
I don't build a thing that's gonna
be a slum in 20 years...

30:21.361 --> 30:23.195
...and I won't doze those hills.

30:23.363 --> 30:26.031
What I build conforms to the land.

30:26.533 --> 30:29.284
And you can't hear the toilets flush next door.

30:30.453 --> 30:33.288
You want our help,
you'll have to let me work on it.

30:34.999 --> 30:37.501
AIMES:
Well, up to a point, I want your help.

30:37.710 --> 30:40.087
PAUL:
Up to a point, I'll give it.

31:31.681 --> 31:33.724
When do I get a look-see?

31:34.809 --> 31:36.768
PAUL:
In a couple days.

31:37.228 --> 31:39.938
Guard says you were here
till after midnight last night.

31:40.106 --> 31:41.607
Yeah. That's the way I work.

31:42.358 --> 31:44.151
Somebody once said...

31:44.360 --> 31:46.737
I forget who.
- That he never looked back...

31:46.905 --> 31:49.197
...because something might
be gaining on him.

31:50.199 --> 31:51.867
What's gaining on you, Paul?

31:53.703 --> 31:55.913
Twenty million dollar investment.
What else?

31:56.623 --> 32:00.751
Well, I was gonna ask you
to have dinner with me at the club...

32:00.919 --> 32:02.836
...but I don't think
you'd be very good company.

32:03.004 --> 32:04.212
No, I don't think I would.

32:04.422 --> 32:08.592
It might amuse you, though. Being from New
York, maybe you never seen a club like this.

32:08.760 --> 32:11.970
It's a gun club. We shoot guns.

32:16.392 --> 32:20.062
So goddamn much hoopla
from the gun control people.

32:20.313 --> 32:22.397
Half the nation's scared to even hold a gun!

32:22.565 --> 32:25.275
You know, like it was a snake,
it was gonna bite you or something.

32:25.443 --> 32:27.569
Hell, a gun is just a tool...

32:28.571 --> 32:31.114
...like a hammer or an ax.

32:31.532 --> 32:34.117
Wasn't long ago,
used to put food on the table...

32:34.327 --> 32:38.246
...keep foxes out of the chicken coop,
rustlers off the range...

32:38.456 --> 32:39.665
...bandits out of the bank.

32:39.832 --> 32:42.042
Paul, how long since
you held a pistol in your hand?

32:43.336 --> 32:46.672
- A long time.
- Hm.

32:47.340 --> 32:50.258
- Which war was yours, Korea?
- Yeah.

32:50.593 --> 32:52.844
- See much action?
- A little.

32:53.096 --> 32:54.513
Were you infantry?

32:56.265 --> 32:59.017
- I was a CO in a medical unit.
- Oh.

32:59.185 --> 33:01.311
Commanding officer, huh?

33:01.980 --> 33:04.439
Conscientious objector.

33:05.274 --> 33:06.733
Oh, Christ.

33:06.943 --> 33:10.654
What a guest to bring to a gun club. Heh.

33:10.822 --> 33:12.781
You're probably one
of them knee-jerk liberals...

33:12.949 --> 33:17.369
...thinks us gun boys shoot our guns
because it's an extension of our penises.

33:17.912 --> 33:19.830
I never thought about it that way...

33:20.164 --> 33:21.498
...but it could be true.

33:22.083 --> 33:23.834
Well, maybe it is...

33:24.293 --> 33:26.253
...but this is gun country.

33:26.421 --> 33:28.588
Can't even own a handgun in New York City.

33:28.756 --> 33:31.049
Out here, I hardly know a man
that doesn't own one.

33:31.426 --> 33:33.051
And I'll tell you something...

33:33.219 --> 33:35.554
...unlike your city, we can walk our streets...

33:35.722 --> 33:37.889
...and through our parks at night and feel safe.

33:38.182 --> 33:42.519
Muggers operating out here,
they'd just plain get their asses blown off.

33:42.854 --> 33:45.564
Here. Slip these on.

33:46.024 --> 33:48.900
All righty. This is a percussion pistol.

33:49.110 --> 33:50.610
1842.

33:54.532 --> 33:56.825
You ever handled one of those before?

33:58.453 --> 33:59.995
You know how to fire it?

34:00.705 --> 34:02.080
Watch the kick.

34:02.290 --> 34:05.125
Boy, you're gonna think that
your arm's gonna hit the ceiling.

34:15.386 --> 34:16.928
Goddamn!

34:17.138 --> 34:18.929
Paul, you hit dead center!

34:19.389 --> 34:21.224
Mind if I try this Hogleg Colt?

34:21.391 --> 34:22.768
No.

34:22.935 --> 34:26.021
Well, you a peculiar
conscientious objector.

34:26.522 --> 34:28.440
- These notches for real?
- Yeah.

34:28.608 --> 34:31.985
Belonged to a gunfighter
named Candy Dan, 1890.

34:32.152 --> 34:35.112
Hm. I do know something about
guns, Aimes.

34:35.281 --> 34:38.033
I grew up with them.
All kinds of guns.

34:38.993 --> 34:40.911
You see, my father was a hunter.

34:41.161 --> 34:43.871
I guess out here you'd call him a gunman.

34:44.165 --> 34:46.750
My mother was the other side of the coin.

34:48.085 --> 34:51.045
When my father was killed
in a hunting accident...

34:52.130 --> 34:54.424
Some fool mistook him
for a deer, you see.

34:55.092 --> 34:56.927
- My mother won the toss.

34:57.220 --> 34:59.346
I never touched a gun since.

35:01.140 --> 35:03.100
I loved my father.

35:15.029 --> 35:16.905
There are your hills.

35:17.949 --> 35:20.367
Every house has a part
of one for a backyard...

35:20.535 --> 35:22.119
...for kids, dogs, horses.

35:22.703 --> 35:25.789
Four hundred houses,
100 more than you allowed for...

35:25.998 --> 35:28.041
...and you still have 12 hills.

35:30.378 --> 35:32.587
I'm catching the 10:40
back to New York.

35:33.214 --> 35:34.881
What do I tell them?

35:36.175 --> 35:37.968
You tell them I'll buy it if they will.

35:58.239 --> 35:59.990
You're checking this bag
through, aren't you?

36:00.408 --> 36:01.783
- Yeah.
- Good.

36:01.993 --> 36:04.870
Let me slip a little
going-away present in there for you.

36:06.789 --> 36:07.914
Thank you.

36:13.171 --> 36:15.672
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Trans World Airlines Flight 63...

36:15.840 --> 36:19.301
...from Tucson to New York is now boarding...
- Good morning, sir. How are you today?

36:19.719 --> 36:21.052
Checking one bag?

36:21.262 --> 36:24.806
Paul, I can't thank you enough
for what you did for me.

36:25.016 --> 36:29.811
I want you to know if you ever
get tired of living in that toilet...

36:30.563 --> 36:32.189
...you're welcome here.

36:34.650 --> 36:36.902
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Trans World airlines Flight 7...

36:37.069 --> 36:39.613
...to London and Frankfurt
is now boarding.

36:39.780 --> 36:42.282
Passengers should proceed to Gate 11...

36:42.450 --> 36:44.159
JACK: Welcome home, Dad.
- Hi, Jack.

36:44.327 --> 36:46.453
I halfway expected to see Carol.

36:46.871 --> 36:48.955
Come on. Let's go get your bags.

36:50.416 --> 36:51.708
What is it?

36:53.169 --> 36:55.253
She's in the hospital.

36:57.757 --> 36:59.424
When I last spoke to you on the phone...

36:59.592 --> 37:02.385
...you said she was feeling better
after coming back from the shore.

37:04.222 --> 37:07.224
Well, I didn't see any need to get you
all disturbed on a long-distance call.

37:07.391 --> 37:11.561
Will Mr. Cory, a passenger
on Trans World Airlines Flight 100...

37:11.729 --> 37:13.855
...from Vancouver, please report to...

37:14.023 --> 37:15.899
Oh, come on, Dad, don't do a number...

37:16.400 --> 37:18.026
Don't do a number on me.

37:18.402 --> 37:20.862
Look, there was nothing you could do.

37:21.656 --> 37:24.866
They haven't even let me see her
for two days.

37:27.328 --> 37:29.955
They tried insulin shock yesterday.

37:30.248 --> 37:32.457
She's not responding.

37:33.501 --> 37:36.419
You want the technical jargon?
I can reel off yards of it:

37:36.754 --> 37:41.758
Catatonia, dementia praecox,
passive schizoid paranoia.

37:43.177 --> 37:47.138
It all boils down to the fact that she's had
an experience that she can't face...

37:47.306 --> 37:49.849
...and she's running away from it
inside herself.

37:50.017 --> 37:53.436
Will Mrs. Lager, a passenger
on Trans World Airlines...

37:53.604 --> 37:55.021
...Flight 45 to Paris...

37:55.231 --> 37:57.816
...please contact the information desk...

37:57.984 --> 37:59.859
You didn't handle her right, Jack.

38:00.861 --> 38:02.946
Aw, Christ, Dad.

38:04.198 --> 38:06.199
I'll get other doctors.

38:06.701 --> 38:10.787
- Who are these goddamn doctors you have?
- They're good doctors.

38:14.125 --> 38:16.584
[VOICE BREAKING]
Dad, she's almost a goddamn vegetable.

38:49.285 --> 38:52.287
If you don't sign the papers, what happens?

38:53.998 --> 38:57.375
I guess they keep her in the hospital
until the insurance runs out.

38:57.543 --> 38:58.835
That won't be too long.

38:59.003 --> 39:02.714
If you sign the papers
and she's committed, what then?

39:04.050 --> 39:07.844
Well, I've got an insurance policy
that covers it up to about 600 a month.

39:08.262 --> 39:11.306
They've recommended
a sanatorium out in Long Island.

39:12.308 --> 39:14.017
Jack...

39:15.519 --> 39:18.313
This commitment,
is it a one-way thing?

39:19.690 --> 39:22.275
Nobody can answer that, Dad.

39:23.694 --> 39:25.528
You wanna know what they are?

39:25.696 --> 39:28.198
They're statistics on a police blotter.

39:28.741 --> 39:31.868
Mom and Carol, along with
thousands of other people.

39:32.453 --> 39:35.246
And there is nothing
that we can do to stop it.

39:36.040 --> 39:37.791
Nothing but cut and run.

42:02.269 --> 42:04.270
[BOTH LAUGHING]

42:06.273 --> 42:10.735
Oh, what a bummer, man. That was
the worst fucking movie I've ever seen.

42:33.008 --> 42:35.009
[SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE]

43:41.785 --> 43:43.244
MAN:
You got money, man?

43:47.791 --> 43:49.125
Shit, I'll kill you!

43:49.335 --> 43:51.210
Give me your money
or I'll bust you up!

44:06.393 --> 44:08.144
[RETCHING]

44:35.130 --> 44:38.466
Oh, Jesus.

44:38.676 --> 44:40.385
Jesus Christ.

44:40.594 --> 44:43.471
Ohh. Oh, Jesus.

44:43.722 --> 44:45.723
[GRUNTING]

45:00.364 --> 45:02.365
[VOMITING]

45:08.163 --> 45:10.164
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

45:18.465 --> 45:19.590
[SNEEZES]

45:19.758 --> 45:21.718
Good morning, inspector.

45:22.886 --> 45:25.012
Good morning. What do we got?

45:25.180 --> 45:27.765
We got a corpse down here,
one bullet hole in his chest.

45:28.016 --> 45:31.894
Fellow over there was jogging through the park
at daybreak, found him on the path here.

45:32.438 --> 45:36.023
OCHOA: You got a make on the dead man?
- Yeah. His name is Thomas Leroy Marston.

45:36.191 --> 45:38.276
He had a parole card,
we got a radio check on that.

45:38.444 --> 45:41.571
He served 42 months of
a five-year hitch for grand larceny.

45:41.739 --> 45:44.198
He's a drug addict.
He's probably popping smack again.

45:44.366 --> 45:45.908
There's punctures, both arms.

45:46.076 --> 45:48.578
We found this on the grass next to him.

45:48.787 --> 45:50.621
Thing hasn't been fired.

45:51.123 --> 45:53.249
Deceased had a gun clip on his belt.

45:53.417 --> 45:54.625
Think it must be his.

45:56.211 --> 45:59.881
What would you say
if I suggested that he tried a heist...

46:00.215 --> 46:01.466
...he got shot for his trouble?

46:01.633 --> 46:04.260
Maybe two guys trying
to heist each other.

46:04.511 --> 46:06.888
No, no. This man wasn't robbed.

46:07.264 --> 46:09.307
Still has money in his wallet.

46:31.914 --> 46:33.623
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

46:35.042 --> 46:36.667
HENRY: Good morning, Paul.
- Good morning.

46:36.877 --> 46:39.545
SAM: Hi, Paul. Morning.
- Morning, Sam.

46:40.214 --> 46:43.883
Well, we've marked it out
as you've indicated.

46:44.551 --> 46:46.385
It's beautiful.

46:46.553 --> 46:48.095
What's our profit?

46:48.931 --> 46:52.683
Uh... Not quite three million,
but I believe that our investment...

46:52.851 --> 46:54.393
...can be amortized in two years...

46:54.561 --> 46:56.896
...and it is a showplace operation.

46:57.064 --> 46:58.815
Look at all that wasted space.

46:59.024 --> 47:00.608
Jainchill loves those hills.

47:00.859 --> 47:03.444
Besides, it's a take-it-or-leave-it proposition.

47:03.612 --> 47:06.113
Well, it's too pretty to leave.

47:07.157 --> 47:09.116
Okay. I'll run it for the board.

47:09.368 --> 47:12.036
- May need your help, Paul.
- Okay.

47:13.914 --> 47:16.666
Oh, Tucson agreed with you.
You look well.

47:17.501 --> 47:20.336
I feel, uh... Good.

47:35.018 --> 47:36.519
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

48:24.860 --> 48:26.861
[DOG BARKING]

48:35.787 --> 48:37.788
[SIREN WAILING]

48:40.208 --> 48:42.209
[REPORTERS CLAMORING]

48:51.053 --> 48:53.804
HANK:
Was he a white man or a black man?

48:53.972 --> 48:55.306
MAN:
I just don't know!

48:55.474 --> 48:57.558
HANK:
Come on. They were under that streetlight.

48:57.726 --> 49:00.811
MAN: I wasn't seeing too good.
I had blood in my eyes.

49:00.979 --> 49:02.855
Well, was he tall? Short?

49:03.023 --> 49:04.607
Thin? Fat?

49:05.192 --> 49:07.735
Hank. Forget it, huh?

49:08.195 --> 49:10.237
Ride the ambulance to the morgue.

49:11.365 --> 49:13.908
When they get the slugs
out of those bodies...

49:14.159 --> 49:16.994
...run them over to the lab for ballistics.

49:18.872 --> 49:20.081
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

49:24.461 --> 49:25.962
You saw him pretty good, didn't you?

49:28.966 --> 49:30.800
You're full of shit.

50:33.405 --> 50:34.447
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

50:37.659 --> 50:39.326
[JACK GRUNTS]

50:40.120 --> 50:42.997
You know, if we had the brains
to live here in the country...

50:43.165 --> 50:45.458
...we wouldn't be here
for the reason we are today.

50:46.793 --> 50:49.253
We'd be going into
the city to work.

50:49.671 --> 50:52.965
And Mom and Carol would be safe at home,
waiting for us to come back.

50:53.592 --> 50:55.843
Nothing to do but cut and run, huh?

50:56.720 --> 50:58.304
Eh, what else?

50:58.680 --> 51:02.683
What about the old American
social custom of self-defense?

51:03.393 --> 51:06.854
If the police don't defend us,
maybe we ought to do it ourselves.

51:08.190 --> 51:10.775
We're not pioneers anymore, Dad.

51:12.152 --> 51:13.819
What are we, Jack?

51:13.987 --> 51:15.237
What do you mean?

51:15.864 --> 51:18.908
I mean, if we're not pioneers,
what have we become?

51:20.035 --> 51:21.827
What do you call people...

51:22.996 --> 51:25.956
...who, when they're faced
with a condition of fear...

51:26.249 --> 51:30.419
...do nothing about it,
they just run and hide?

51:31.213 --> 51:32.838
Civilized?

51:35.467 --> 51:36.509
[SIGHS]

51:36.676 --> 51:38.302
No.

51:42.390 --> 51:44.183
Ladies and gentlemen...

51:44.601 --> 51:47.436
...we have to start
this investigation somewhere...

51:47.979 --> 51:49.855
...so let's start here.

51:51.983 --> 51:53.359
[COUGHS]

51:54.152 --> 51:55.402
[CLEARS THROAT]

51:55.570 --> 51:56.821
Motive:

51:57.280 --> 51:58.697
Revenge.

51:59.241 --> 52:01.200
I want the records checked.

52:01.618 --> 52:03.452
Go back, say, uh...

52:03.662 --> 52:05.329
Three months.

52:06.248 --> 52:08.249
Limit it to homicide.

52:08.750 --> 52:10.751
We could be looking for
a man who's had a member...

52:10.919 --> 52:14.046
...or members of his family
killed by muggers.

52:17.300 --> 52:19.927
Now, he shoots that pistol pretty good.

52:20.345 --> 52:21.554
Right?

52:22.055 --> 52:23.639
Okay.

52:24.099 --> 52:25.766
Combat veteran.

52:26.101 --> 52:28.686
So put Vietnam vets
at the top of the list...

52:28.895 --> 52:31.147
...because they're youngest
and toughest.

52:31.398 --> 52:35.192
Then you can work your way
through Korea and World War II.

52:35.360 --> 52:36.902
WOMAN:
Oh, my God!

52:38.405 --> 52:39.697
Who said that?

52:39.948 --> 52:41.240
Hmm?

52:42.242 --> 52:44.660
Well, whoever said it,
you're right on the button.

52:45.287 --> 52:49.707
By God and Jesus Christ,
it's impossible...

52:50.625 --> 52:53.085
...but until we find a shortcut...

52:53.420 --> 52:55.462
...we'll at least keep busy.

52:56.047 --> 52:59.967
So when the media demands to know
what we are doing to apprehend the vigilante...

53:00.594 --> 53:04.471
...we'll tell them we have definite clues.

53:05.599 --> 53:06.932
Okay?

53:08.059 --> 53:11.395
We won't tell them we have
about a thousand definite clues.

55:21.526 --> 55:23.527
[GUNSHOT]

55:49.429 --> 55:50.596
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

55:53.141 --> 55:55.351
MAN 1:
There's a body in there! Two of them!

56:11.284 --> 56:13.577
MAN 2: Where'd he go?
- Did anybody see what he looked like?

56:13.787 --> 56:15.662
We're in Police Commissioner Dryer's office...

56:15.830 --> 56:19.166
...waiting for a press conference
scheduled by Commissioner Dryer.

56:19.376 --> 56:22.669
Last night, there was another double killing,
which appears to be the work...

56:22.837 --> 56:26.382
...of the person New York news media
have dubbed "The Vigilante."

56:26.549 --> 56:28.550
[SPEAKING IN ITALIAN]

56:32.931 --> 56:34.932
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

56:38.478 --> 56:40.896
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

56:41.106 --> 56:42.773
ANNOUNCER:
This will be the first official statement...

56:42.941 --> 56:45.150
...from Commissioner Dryer
on the Vigilante killings.

56:45.318 --> 56:47.653
I can see the commissioner now
as he walks past...

56:47.821 --> 56:52.199
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen.
With me is Inspector Frank Ochoa...

56:53.284 --> 56:56.078
...who has been placed in command
of a police detail...

56:56.246 --> 57:01.125
...assigned to what we've all
been calling the Vigilante murders.

57:01.334 --> 57:05.462
Now, it has been confirmed
by our ballistics laboratory...

57:06.631 --> 57:08.841
...that the same gun, a.32 pistol...

57:09.050 --> 57:12.469
...which was used
in the previous three homicides...

57:12.679 --> 57:16.014
...was used last night in a shooting
aboard a subway train.

57:17.142 --> 57:21.603
Now, I know that this person
has captured the imagination...

57:21.813 --> 57:23.897
...of many people in our city...

57:24.190 --> 57:26.066
...and I wanna say to our citizens:

57:27.152 --> 57:31.280
Murder is no answer
to crime in this city.

57:31.448 --> 57:34.116
Crime is a police responsibility...

57:35.368 --> 57:38.245
...and if this person
is listening to my voice...

57:39.080 --> 57:42.207
...I urge him
in the name of law and order...

57:43.334 --> 57:48.547
...to desist from this one-man crusade
and turn himself in to the police.

57:49.507 --> 57:52.217
He'll be given fair treatment.

57:52.385 --> 57:54.470
How do you like it?
That's our police commissioner...

57:54.637 --> 57:56.597
...that's Ryder, the king of clichÃ©s.

57:56.764 --> 57:59.433
REPORTER 1:vigilante's identification?
- No comment at this time.

57:59.642 --> 58:02.269
REPORTER 2:
Do you think this man's crazy?

58:02.562 --> 58:05.105
OCHOA:
Well, he's got a wire down, all right...

58:05.315 --> 58:08.150
...but I don't believe
we're dealing with a raving maniac.

58:08.359 --> 58:11.737
REPORTER 3: Commissioner, it's rumored
that the rate of street muggings has dropped...

58:11.905 --> 58:14.406
...since The Vigilante
became headline news. Is that true?

58:14.574 --> 58:15.616
Not true.

58:15.867 --> 58:17.951
REPORTER 4:
If it were true, would you announce it, sir?

58:18.119 --> 58:20.829
Or are you afraid that would stimulate
imitators of The Vigilante?

58:20.997 --> 58:23.999
I don't wanna get into
these hypothetical questions.

58:24.250 --> 58:27.294
Mm. I bet muggings are down,
they're afraid to tell us.

58:27.545 --> 58:31.131
There's only one way to find out:
Take a walk on Columbus Avenue tonight.

58:31.341 --> 58:34.635
Thanks a lot, Paul, I think
I'll wait for the official report.

58:34.802 --> 58:36.970
DRYER [ON TV]:
- Successful, regardless of the...

58:38.973 --> 58:40.974
[PHONE RINGS]

58:41.726 --> 58:43.268
Yes?

58:44.229 --> 58:48.148
Ah. You wanna confess
to the Vigilante killings?

58:48.858 --> 58:50.108
All right.

58:50.443 --> 58:52.486
I'll put you through to Rosenberg.

58:52.654 --> 58:55.072
He's in charge of confessions today.

58:55.573 --> 58:57.616
That's the 23rd.

58:57.951 --> 58:59.284
Put him through.

58:59.911 --> 59:03.121
We couldn't get any prints
off The Vigilante's groceries.

59:03.331 --> 59:06.875
- Wasn't there a sales slip?
- Yeah. Here.

59:08.586 --> 59:11.213
D'Agostino's.

59:11.673 --> 59:13.090
Mm-hm.

59:14.551 --> 59:18.345
Some of this code must identify
the particular store.

59:18.721 --> 59:20.389
Find out where it is.

59:20.640 --> 59:22.099
When we get the records...

59:22.267 --> 59:26.019
...check on families that have had
somebody killed by muggers.

59:26.229 --> 59:29.690
Let's put them through the computer
and see if any of them live near this store.

59:31.442 --> 59:35.445
People are inclined to buy groceries
in their own neighborhoods.

59:36.698 --> 59:39.700
PAUL: Hi, Jack. Come on. Come on in.
- Dad.

59:39.867 --> 59:40.909
Make yourself a drink.

59:41.077 --> 59:43.078
[UPBEAT MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

59:43.496 --> 59:45.080
Hey, what do you think?

59:45.373 --> 59:46.665
The new paint?

59:48.376 --> 59:52.713
- Well, it's a little hard on the eyes, but...
- Hard on the eyes? It's cheerful.

59:54.257 --> 59:55.507
[TURNS MUSIC DOWN]

59:55.967 --> 59:59.845
Hey, Jack. Turn it back up. I can't hear.

01:00:01.973 --> 01:00:03.640
[TURNS MUSIC UP]

01:00:03.850 --> 01:00:06.184
We got liver and spaghetti for dinner.

01:00:06.352 --> 01:00:08.020
How do you like your liver done?

01:00:08.313 --> 01:00:09.980
- Uh...
- Hey, no drink?

01:00:10.189 --> 01:00:11.481
Let me make you one.

01:00:12.734 --> 01:00:15.444
No. Dad... Listen, that's all right.
I'll get it myself.

01:00:16.696 --> 01:00:18.071
I, uh...

01:00:19.198 --> 01:00:21.116
I saw Carol today.

01:00:21.784 --> 01:00:24.369
- Aren't you gonna ask how she's doing?
- I know how she's doing.

01:00:24.537 --> 01:00:26.330
I went up to see her yesterday.

01:00:27.999 --> 01:00:29.750
Then what the hell
are you so high about?

01:00:29.959 --> 01:00:32.794
What the hell you want me to do,
moan and groan for the rest of my life?

01:00:36.132 --> 01:00:37.674
How do you want your liver, medium?

01:00:39.552 --> 01:00:42.095
Medium. I'll make it medium.

01:00:57.904 --> 01:01:00.822
- Hey, there goes the pussy posse.
WOMAN: Ha-ha-ha!

01:01:18.341 --> 01:01:21.134
[CHATTERING]

01:02:29.871 --> 01:02:31.830
Hey, mister, got a match?

01:02:35.042 --> 01:02:36.084
Yeah.

01:02:36.335 --> 01:02:37.836
MAN 1:
What else you got?

01:02:41.424 --> 01:02:42.924
Let's see the money, man.

01:02:44.260 --> 01:02:46.303
- You'll have to take it.
MAN 2: Shit.

01:02:46.721 --> 01:02:48.638
[GUNSHOTS]

01:03:08.826 --> 01:03:10.827
[WOMEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

01:03:25.802 --> 01:03:27.219
He went that way.

01:04:51.053 --> 01:04:52.762
Who rode the ambulance with him?

01:04:53.764 --> 01:04:54.890
I did.

01:04:55.725 --> 01:04:56.850
OCHOA:
Well?

01:04:57.476 --> 01:05:00.687
- Was he talking?
- He said he cut whoever it was that shot him.

01:05:00.897 --> 01:05:04.399
Exact words:
"I cut that motherfucker. I hit him."

01:05:05.943 --> 01:05:08.737
Can't save him.
Too much internal bleeding.

01:05:09.155 --> 01:05:10.906
One slug chewed up the liver.

01:05:11.574 --> 01:05:12.782
Here.

01:05:17.496 --> 01:05:18.538
.32's.

01:05:20.249 --> 01:05:24.210
MAN [ON TV]: City tonight,
the mysterious Vigilante is in the news again.

01:05:24.420 --> 01:05:28.214
A little more than two hours ago,
in an 8th Avenue subway underpass...

01:05:28.382 --> 01:05:30.634
...two men were shot.
One died on the spot.

01:05:30.801 --> 01:05:33.303
The other managed to reach
the street before he collapsed.

01:05:33.471 --> 01:05:35.805
He died shortly afterward in the hospital.

01:05:36.432 --> 01:05:41.102
The two men have been identified
as Joseph Roscoe Adams and George Reech.

01:05:41.270 --> 01:05:43.146
Both had long criminal records.

01:05:43.356 --> 01:05:46.983
The Vigilante himself
may have been wounded.

01:05:47.777 --> 01:05:51.696
The actions of The Vigilante,
as lawless as they may be...

01:05:51.948 --> 01:05:56.201
...seem to be giving others
new attitudes toward crime in the streets.

01:05:56.452 --> 01:05:59.663
Instead of helplessly allowing themselves
to be mugged and robbed...

01:05:59.872 --> 01:06:01.539
...a few are fighting back.

01:06:01.749 --> 01:06:04.542
I have with me
Mrs. Alma Lee Brown...

01:06:04.710 --> 01:06:07.837
...who today successfully defended
herself against two muggers...

01:06:08.005 --> 01:06:09.506
...with an unusual weapon.

01:06:09.674 --> 01:06:13.551
Mrs. Brown, would you tell us
how you drove off your attackers today?

01:06:13.719 --> 01:06:15.220
MRS. BROWN:
With a hatpin!

01:06:15.972 --> 01:06:20.350
- You ever seen a hatpin?
REPORTER 1: I can't say that I have.

01:06:20.518 --> 01:06:24.270
MRS. BROWN: Well, that's what we used
to use to hold our hats on with, ha, ha...

01:06:24.438 --> 01:06:28.191
...and I ain't got no gun
like this Vigilante fellow...

01:06:28.693 --> 01:06:33.279
...but I went to my closet, and everybody
better look out for me from now on.

01:06:33.447 --> 01:06:34.489
[CROWD WHOOPS ON TV]

01:06:34.657 --> 01:06:38.535
Because I've been robbed too many times,
and I've had enough!

01:06:39.078 --> 01:06:41.246
REPORTER 2: Some of the men
building this skyscraper...

01:06:41.414 --> 01:06:43.915
...made what you might call
a citizens' arrest today.

01:06:44.125 --> 01:06:46.960
I'll ask Andrew McCabe,
one of the foremen, to tell you about it.

01:06:47.545 --> 01:06:50.755
Me and my crew was working
down in the hole.

01:06:50.923 --> 01:06:53.383
One of the boys
up on the steel yelled down:

01:06:53.551 --> 01:06:55.260
"There's a mugging going on!"

01:06:55.469 --> 01:06:59.389
So we come out of the hole and through
the gate, and we caught this guy running.

01:06:59.557 --> 01:07:02.559
And we roughed him up a little bit
before the police came.

01:07:02.768 --> 01:07:05.603
REPORTER 2: The hospital report
says the man had two broken arms...

01:07:05.771 --> 01:07:08.982
...a broken jaw, and cracked ribs.
- No kidding? Jeez.

01:07:09.191 --> 01:07:11.276
Poor guy must have fell down.

01:07:12.111 --> 01:07:14.821
Walking distances from D'Agostino's:

01:07:14.989 --> 01:07:19.034
Two blocks crosstown,
six short blocks uptown and downtown.

01:07:19.326 --> 01:07:21.828
I mean, that's how far
I'd be willing to walk to a market.

01:07:21.996 --> 01:07:25.957
Ahem. Good. Very good, Miss Gemetti.

01:07:26.167 --> 01:07:28.460
GEMETTI:
We have 12 families living within this area...

01:07:28.627 --> 01:07:31.421
...who have suffered a death
in the family in the past three months...

01:07:31.589 --> 01:07:34.549
...from mugging, stabbing,
shooting, assault.

01:07:34.717 --> 01:07:37.260
Two of these families
have no male members.

01:07:37.428 --> 01:07:40.221
One family has only
an 80-year-old grandfather.

01:07:40.389 --> 01:07:42.474
That leaves nine families.

01:07:42.725 --> 01:07:45.685
Total number of male persons
in these families...

01:07:45.853 --> 01:07:50.065
...who are old enough to have served
in the Vietnam War, Korea, or World War II...

01:07:50.232 --> 01:07:52.233
...comes to 14.

01:07:53.569 --> 01:07:57.572
Wild. It's a real wild shot...

01:07:58.741 --> 01:08:03.661
...but the fact is that The Vigilante
plugged his first victim in Riverside Park...

01:08:03.829 --> 01:08:08.166
...exactly two and one half blocks
from that D'Agostino market.

01:08:08.793 --> 01:08:12.837
Even if all these guys are clean,
we still can't ignore that coincidence.

01:08:13.339 --> 01:08:14.547
No, sir.

01:08:15.132 --> 01:08:17.258
Our friend lives in that neighborhood.

01:08:17.426 --> 01:08:21.763
But, Frank, he was on a subway
with groceries five miles uptown.

01:08:22.598 --> 01:08:26.475
There's no better come-on for a mugging
than a guy with a bagful of groceries.

01:08:26.685 --> 01:08:30.354
Means he's got some money in his pocket
and his hands are occupied.

01:08:30.731 --> 01:08:33.899
He might have been carrying
those groceries for hours.

01:08:35.903 --> 01:08:38.279
I want a preliminary line
on these names.

01:08:38.447 --> 01:08:44.702
Where they work, service record,
reputation, police record, if any.

01:08:45.328 --> 01:08:48.497
And I want it fast.

01:08:49.125 --> 01:08:52.502
You know, like today, huh?

01:08:53.754 --> 01:08:57.131
WOMAN: It's probably having
as much effect on the total crime picture...

01:08:57.299 --> 01:08:59.175
...as putting a Band-Aid on a leper.

01:08:59.343 --> 01:09:03.638
SAM: Wait a minute, I don't know about that, a
mugger's gonna think twice about who he hits.

01:09:03.805 --> 01:09:06.015
Sure. They're hitting more old ladies,
that's why.

01:09:06.183 --> 01:09:08.852
Paul, how you doing?
Let me get you a drink.

01:09:11.604 --> 01:09:13.398
MAN:
Tell you one thing: The guy's a racist.

01:09:13.607 --> 01:09:15.399
You notice he kills
more blacks than whites.

01:09:15.568 --> 01:09:17.944
Oh, for Pete's sake, more blacks
are muggers than whites.

01:09:18.112 --> 01:09:20.863
What do you want us to do,
increase the proportion of white muggers...

01:09:21.031 --> 01:09:22.866
...so we'll have racial equality
among muggers?

01:09:23.033 --> 01:09:26.452
Racial equality among muggers?
Ooh. I love it!

01:09:26.662 --> 01:09:28.705
He hasn't been the same
since that terrible incident.

01:09:56.609 --> 01:09:58.610
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

01:10:03.782 --> 01:10:08.578
- Who we got here?
- A guy named Paul... Kersey.

01:10:08.787 --> 01:10:10.705
His wife was murdered
in their apartment.

01:10:10.873 --> 01:10:13.625
Interesting detail:
The attackers, three of them...

01:10:13.834 --> 01:10:16.377
...gained entrance to the apartment
by posing as delivery boys...

01:10:16.545 --> 01:10:20.256
...from our D'Agostino's market,
where The Vigilante buys his groceries.

01:10:20.966 --> 01:10:22.091
What else about him?

01:10:22.718 --> 01:10:24.302
He lives alone now.

01:10:24.511 --> 01:10:27.722
Development engineer
for the Blue Ridge corporation.

01:10:27.973 --> 01:10:30.016
Served in Korea, medical corps.

01:10:30.601 --> 01:10:32.435
Conscientious objector.

01:10:32.603 --> 01:10:36.606
No police record.
Credits, reputation excellent.

01:10:37.316 --> 01:10:40.109
Conscientious objectors
are unlikely vigilantes.

01:10:40.903 --> 01:10:44.030
- We got a finger?
- Yeah. Over there.

01:10:44.240 --> 01:10:47.325
Patrolman Joe Charles.

01:10:47.493 --> 01:10:48.660
Good.

01:10:52.748 --> 01:10:54.123
Good morning, Mr. Kersey.

01:10:54.875 --> 01:10:56.417
Joe Charles, Mr. Kersey.

01:10:56.627 --> 01:10:58.169
PAUL:
Oh, yes, of course.

01:10:58.337 --> 01:11:00.380
CHARLES:
How do you do? Good to see you again.

01:11:00.589 --> 01:11:02.173
How's your daughter?

01:11:02.758 --> 01:11:04.217
The same.

01:11:04.760 --> 01:11:06.302
Take care.

01:11:09.556 --> 01:11:11.015
Follow him.

01:11:23.862 --> 01:11:25.655
Yes, I'll see to that, Mrs. Cohen.

01:11:25.823 --> 01:11:27.740
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

01:11:28.701 --> 01:11:30.952
Just a moment.
You're not residents here.

01:11:31.161 --> 01:11:32.912
Who do you wish to see?
I'll call up for you.

01:11:33.080 --> 01:11:34.414
No, you won't.

01:11:38.168 --> 01:11:40.169
[KNOCKS]

01:11:49.305 --> 01:11:51.306
[COUGHS]

01:13:18.811 --> 01:13:21.187
MAN:
The district attorney will see you now.

01:13:27.694 --> 01:13:29.695
[COUGHING]

01:13:30.948 --> 01:13:33.825
- Commissioner.
- Frank, you know the district attorney.

01:13:34.952 --> 01:13:37.370
- Mr. Peters.
- Inspector.

01:13:38.789 --> 01:13:41.374
The commissioner says
you have a pretty good suspect.

01:13:41.834 --> 01:13:45.378
Well, he fits the bill in some respects.

01:13:45.838 --> 01:13:49.006
We got a blood sample
from the knife...

01:13:49.174 --> 01:13:52.510
...used on him in the subway
and checked it against the sample...

01:13:52.678 --> 01:13:54.303
...I found in his apartment.

01:13:55.180 --> 01:13:56.472
It narrows it down.

01:13:56.723 --> 01:13:58.724
But in the balance,
he could be the man?

01:13:59.184 --> 01:14:00.351
Yeah.

01:14:00.936 --> 01:14:02.728
Yeah, he could be.

01:14:03.397 --> 01:14:04.730
DRYER:
Frank...

01:14:06.108 --> 01:14:09.402
Suppose this Paul Kersey is The Vigilante.

01:14:09.945 --> 01:14:11.904
All right. Let's say that.

01:14:14.825 --> 01:14:16.033
We don't want him.

01:14:18.537 --> 01:14:19.912
Okay.

01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:24.834
Inspector, on my desk, I have a statistic
red-hot out of the computer.

01:14:25.043 --> 01:14:26.085
DRYER:
Mm-hm.

01:14:26.253 --> 01:14:29.297
Mugging has gone down
by how much, sir?

01:14:29.840 --> 01:14:33.759
From 950 a week
to 470 reported last week.

01:14:33.927 --> 01:14:35.928
DRYER: You understand
not too many people know that.

01:14:36.638 --> 01:14:39.348
And you wanna keep it that way, huh?

01:14:39.516 --> 01:14:42.018
Oh, no, we have to keep it
that way, inspector.

01:14:42.978 --> 01:14:44.729
This whole city would explode.

01:14:44.938 --> 01:14:48.816
We'd have vigilantes out in the street
killing anybody who even looked greasy.

01:14:49.359 --> 01:14:53.112
- You can see that.
- We want this man to quit, desist...

01:14:53.614 --> 01:14:56.824
...go away. To stop.

01:14:59.328 --> 01:15:01.412
So the mugging rate can go up?

01:15:03.123 --> 01:15:05.374
If I arrest him, wouldn't that
get him off the streets?

01:15:05.542 --> 01:15:07.835
My God, man. I don't want
a martyr on my hands.

01:15:08.003 --> 01:15:11.339
All right. All right.

01:15:11.882 --> 01:15:14.050
I just wanna hear you say it.

01:15:20.098 --> 01:15:21.849
I'll try to scare him off...

01:15:22.559 --> 01:15:24.644
...but that's as far as I'll go.

01:15:24.853 --> 01:15:28.231
That's right, Frank. Scare him off.

01:15:28.607 --> 01:15:29.941
[SCOFFS]

01:15:30.108 --> 01:15:31.901
Scare him off?

01:15:32.110 --> 01:15:33.486
[SIGHS]

01:15:39.826 --> 01:15:41.786
[INTERCOM BUZZES]

01:15:45.958 --> 01:15:46.999
Yes?

01:15:47.167 --> 01:15:49.835
WOMAN: A call for you from a man
who says he's an old friend...

01:15:50.003 --> 01:15:51.754
...and wonders if you'll
recognize his voice.

01:15:51.964 --> 01:15:55.007
Do you want the call that way,
or shall I insist upon his name?

01:15:55.467 --> 01:15:58.177
- Okay, I'll take it.
- I'm putting you through.

01:16:00.931 --> 01:16:03.683
- Hello?
- Is this Paul Kersey?

01:16:03.892 --> 01:16:05.560
Yes. Who's this?

01:16:07.521 --> 01:16:10.565
Mr. Kersey,
you're under police surveillance.

01:16:11.024 --> 01:16:13.109
You're being watched.

01:16:14.319 --> 01:16:16.320
[LINE DISCONNECTS]

01:16:21.493 --> 01:16:24.662
Scare him off. Heh. Ha-ha-ha.

01:16:36.341 --> 01:16:39.135
MAN:
Papers! Papers!

01:16:39.469 --> 01:16:42.471
Read all about The Vigilante!

01:16:43.098 --> 01:16:45.349
Get your papers here!

01:16:45.517 --> 01:16:47.810
Read all about The Vigilante!

01:16:48.186 --> 01:16:49.937
How are you this evening, sir?

01:16:50.105 --> 01:16:52.648
Papers! Papers!

01:16:52.816 --> 01:16:55.234
Read all about The Vigilante!

01:17:11.752 --> 01:17:15.504
OFFICER: All right, you. Get your hands up.
Come on. Hands on the car. Come on.

01:17:15.714 --> 01:17:17.131
Spread your legs.

01:17:25.515 --> 01:17:26.974
Okay. Turn around.

01:17:27.768 --> 01:17:29.810
Let's see some identification.

01:17:35.275 --> 01:17:38.444
- Where do you live?
- 33 Riverside.

01:17:38.737 --> 01:17:41.197
Okay, Mr. Kersey. Sorry to have
roughed you up so much.

01:17:41.365 --> 01:17:43.616
We're looking for a guy
pretty close to your description.

01:17:43.825 --> 01:17:48.079
He's supposed to be armed, and we couldn't
take any chances. I hope you understand.

01:17:49.373 --> 01:17:52.124
Look, if you wanna make a complaint,
I'll give you my number.

01:17:52.376 --> 01:17:53.918
It's all right. Nobody was hurt.

01:17:54.127 --> 01:17:56.837
- Okay, thanks. Good night, Mr. Kersey.
- Night.

01:18:03.136 --> 01:18:04.387
Okay?

01:18:04.971 --> 01:18:06.055
Yeah.

01:18:06.932 --> 01:18:08.224
Okay.

01:18:28.870 --> 01:18:30.955
Went in the building about 10 minutes ago.

01:18:31.123 --> 01:18:33.457
Went to D'Agostino's market first.

01:19:19.045 --> 01:19:21.046
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

01:19:31.057 --> 01:19:33.058
[OCHOA SIGHS]

01:19:33.560 --> 01:19:35.144
Let's check him, huh?

01:19:36.438 --> 01:19:38.689
Go to that phone booth on the corner,
call his number.

01:19:38.857 --> 01:19:40.357
He's up there.

01:19:40.776 --> 01:19:42.401
Check him anyway.

01:19:43.653 --> 01:19:45.738
[MAN MUTTERS INDISTINCTLY]

01:20:33.328 --> 01:20:34.954
[ALL WHOOPING AND LAUGHING]

01:20:56.977 --> 01:20:59.645
MAN 1: Police! I need the phone.
MAN 2: Come on!

01:21:00.355 --> 01:21:02.398
- Who is this guy?
- He must be crazy.

01:21:02.566 --> 01:21:04.608
He said "police."
I didn't see a badge.

01:21:08.154 --> 01:21:09.947
[LINE RINGING]

01:21:11.283 --> 01:21:13.993
I'll call them. I'll call as soon
as he gets off the phone.

01:21:14.160 --> 01:21:17.079
- Thanks, pal.
- Yeah? Up yours!

01:21:23.628 --> 01:21:26.380
No answer. He could be
in the shower or something.

01:21:26.548 --> 01:21:28.048
OCHOA:
Stay here.

01:21:29.175 --> 01:21:31.176
[TIRES SCREECHING]

01:22:21.645 --> 01:22:23.228
[CAR HORNS HONKING]

01:22:24.314 --> 01:22:26.482
- Good night, Mr. Kersey.
- Good night.

01:22:36.409 --> 01:22:38.035
[TIRES SCREECH]

01:22:55.428 --> 01:22:57.596
I'm supposed to meet Paul Kersey.
Has he gone up yet?

01:22:57.764 --> 01:23:01.600
Kersey? Yes, sir. He went up and came down.
Just walked out.

01:23:22.664 --> 01:23:24.164
[TIRES SCREECHING]

01:23:32.048 --> 01:23:35.092
- Where'd you go?
- He didn't show here, did he?

01:23:35.301 --> 01:23:36.969
Can I ask a simple question?

01:23:37.178 --> 01:23:39.388
Is this Paul Kersey the bird?

01:23:40.849 --> 01:23:42.933
I ain't gonna ask any more questions.

01:23:43.226 --> 01:23:45.269
Go home, will you? I don't need you.

01:23:45.437 --> 01:23:46.812
Weird!

01:24:16.718 --> 01:24:20.471
Come on down, motherfucker.
We gonna take you.

01:24:20.680 --> 01:24:24.850
That's right, motherfucker,
and you can't go back up, either.

01:24:25.727 --> 01:24:27.728
[MUGGERS LAUGHING]

01:24:32.776 --> 01:24:35.694
Come on down
and bring us the money, honey.

01:24:35.945 --> 01:24:38.655
How much money you got, honey?

01:24:38.823 --> 01:24:40.824
[LAUGHS]

01:24:44.579 --> 01:24:46.038
What the fuck?

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:48.665
Fuck!

01:25:00.595 --> 01:25:02.596
[GROANS]

01:25:07.435 --> 01:25:09.436
[SIRENS WAILING]

01:25:22.909 --> 01:25:24.868
OFFICER [OVER RADIO]:
Units in the 2-6 precinct.

01:25:25.036 --> 01:25:28.539
A 10-34, 1-2-5 Street
and the West Side Highway.

01:26:33.479 --> 01:26:36.315
[SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE]

01:26:43.198 --> 01:26:44.489
PAUL:
Hey!

01:26:51.456 --> 01:26:52.539
Fill your hand.

01:26:53.833 --> 01:26:55.250
Huh?

01:26:58.463 --> 01:27:00.005
Draw.

01:27:03.343 --> 01:27:05.010
[SIRENS WAILING]

01:27:10.475 --> 01:27:12.476
[ALL CLAMORING]

01:27:13.686 --> 01:27:15.687
[CAR HORN HONKING]

01:27:24.364 --> 01:27:26.365
[SIREN WAILING]

01:27:27.784 --> 01:27:29.785
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

01:27:42.757 --> 01:27:44.258
Where is he, this patrolman?

01:28:00.608 --> 01:28:02.025
- You're Reilly?
- Yes, sir.

01:28:02.193 --> 01:28:03.777
- I'm Ochoa.
- Yes, sir.

01:28:05.947 --> 01:28:08.073
- You were the first man on the scene?
- Yes, sir.

01:28:08.283 --> 01:28:09.324
[SNEEZES]

01:28:09.492 --> 01:28:12.369
- God bless you, sir.
- Never mind that.

01:28:14.205 --> 01:28:16.623
They told me on the radio
you had to see me?

01:28:16.916 --> 01:28:18.417
Paul Kersey.

01:28:19.794 --> 01:28:21.712
You spoke to him
before the ambulance got here?

01:28:21.921 --> 01:28:23.005
No, sir.

01:28:23.965 --> 01:28:25.757
- What did you get?
- His address, sir.

01:28:27.552 --> 01:28:28.927
Is that all?

01:28:31.389 --> 01:28:32.431
Well?

01:28:42.108 --> 01:28:43.859
You enter this on your report?

01:28:44.277 --> 01:28:45.319
Not yet, sir.

01:28:47.447 --> 01:28:48.530
Why not?

01:28:49.449 --> 01:28:50.741
I was, uh...

01:28:50.908 --> 01:28:52.534
...waiting for instructions, sir.

01:28:53.328 --> 01:28:54.578
You never saw it.

01:28:56.581 --> 01:28:57.831
Yes, sir.

01:29:01.127 --> 01:29:03.962
Oh, uh... What's your full name?

01:29:04.172 --> 01:29:06.798
Jackson Reilly, sir. 21 st precinct.

01:29:07.884 --> 01:29:10.886
Okay. I'll remember it.

01:29:23.649 --> 01:29:26.443
REPORTER: Inspector, is it true
that you have The Vigilante in there?

01:29:26.652 --> 01:29:28.737
OCHOA: No.
REPORTER: Well, who have you got there?

01:29:29.405 --> 01:29:31.406
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY OVER PA]

01:29:33.409 --> 01:29:35.452
Are you in charge? How is he?

01:29:35.620 --> 01:29:39.331
Wounds are clean. Nothing vital.
We have a transfusion going on now.

01:29:39.499 --> 01:29:41.708
Soon as we get some blood in him,
we'll sew him up again.

01:29:41.876 --> 01:29:42.918
- Is he in there?
- Yeah.

01:29:43.086 --> 01:29:45.212
- All right if I go in?
- He won't be able to talk much.

01:29:45.380 --> 01:29:48.048
- Can he hear me?
- He is conscious.

01:29:59.143 --> 01:30:01.853
Police. I'd like to have him alone.

01:30:17.036 --> 01:30:19.037
Good evening, Mr. Kersey.

01:30:25.336 --> 01:30:27.295
This is your gun, Mr. Kersey.

01:30:29.549 --> 01:30:31.842
We tried to give you a chance to get rid of it.

01:30:32.176 --> 01:30:33.343
You wouldn't take it.

01:30:34.804 --> 01:30:36.721
Do you hear me okay?

01:30:38.349 --> 01:30:42.060
We have here a peculiar situation,
Mr. Kersey.

01:30:42.603 --> 01:30:48.108
We find it necessary to make you a proposition
since you are not gonna favor us by dying.

01:30:49.152 --> 01:30:53.321
You work for a company with lots of offices.

01:30:54.407 --> 01:30:56.992
Get a transfer to another city...

01:30:57.660 --> 01:30:59.870
...and I'll drop this gun in the river.

01:31:03.958 --> 01:31:08.211
Are we connecting, Mr. Kersey?

01:31:10.089 --> 01:31:12.549
We want you to get out of New York.

01:31:13.259 --> 01:31:15.135
Permanently.

01:31:20.349 --> 01:31:21.725
Inspector.

01:31:25.813 --> 01:31:27.522
By sundown?

01:31:33.404 --> 01:31:34.863
[SNEEZES]

01:31:43.623 --> 01:31:44.873
REPORTER 1: There he is.
REPORTER 2: Here he comes.

01:31:45.082 --> 01:31:46.625
REPORTER 3:
Do you have The Vigilante, inspector?

01:31:46.834 --> 01:31:49.461
REPORTER 4: Can you give us information?
- No!

01:31:49.670 --> 01:31:51.338
Isn't the wounded man The Vigilante?

01:31:51.547 --> 01:31:53.006
No. He's just a mugging victim.

01:31:53.216 --> 01:31:56.176
How do you explain the first reports
that he is The Vigilante?

01:31:56.344 --> 01:31:58.386
False reports. It happens all the time.

01:31:58.596 --> 01:32:00.597
Then The Vigilante's still out there?

01:32:00.765 --> 01:32:02.766
That's right. He's still
out there on the streets.

01:32:02.975 --> 01:32:06.019
- Let me through.
REPORTER 5: Was he shot by The Vigilante?

01:32:17.615 --> 01:32:21.159
WOMAN [OVER PA]: The Amtrak train from
New York to Chicago has arrived on Track 8.

01:32:22.537 --> 01:32:24.246
MAN: Mr. Kersey.
- Paul Kersey.

01:32:24.413 --> 01:32:27.332
Fred Brown. Welcome to Chicago, sir.
Did you have a nice trip?

01:32:27.500 --> 01:32:28.625
Yeah, it was okay.

01:32:28.793 --> 01:32:32.420
Good. I found a nice apartment for you.
I hope you like it. It's on Lake Shore Drive.

01:32:32.588 --> 01:32:36.132
You have a view of Lake Michigan,
morning sun. We've got your office ready too.

01:32:36.342 --> 01:32:38.051
There's a very good golf club,
if you play.

01:32:39.011 --> 01:32:41.846
- Listen, I think you'll enjoy it here.
- Excuse me.

01:32:50.189 --> 01:32:52.190
[CHATTERING AND LAUGHING]

01:33:25.057 --> 01:33:27.058
[English - US - SDH]
